INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|CL', 'The Acura CL is a mid-size luxury coupe that was a staple of Acura''s early 2000s lineup. Early models use a fixed-code system, while later generations transition to Megamos ID13 and later ID48 encrypted chips. Programming for early transponder models is straightforward using standard OBDII tools like the Autel IM608. Always verify if the vehicle has a factory alarm, as it can occasionally interfere with the transponder sync process.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|CSX (Canada)', 'The Acura CSX is a Canada-exclusive compact luxury sedan based on the eighth-generation Honda Civic platform. It primarily utilizes the Honda/Acura G-chip or early proximity systems depending on the trim level and year. Most locksmith tools handle this via the Civic or CSX menu with high success rates in under 10 minutes. Ensure the battery voltage is stable during the ''All Keys Lost'' procedure to prevent BCM communication drops.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|EL (Canada)', 'The Acura EL was a Canadian market predecessor to the CSX, serving as an upscale version of the Honda Civic. Security ranges from non-transponder in very early models to Megamos ID13 and ID48 chips in the later 2000s versions. Programming is generally very easy and reliable using the ''General Honda/Acura'' software selection on most handheld programmers. Watch for worn ignition cylinders which are common on these models and may require mechanical repair before programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|ILX', 'The Acura ILX is an entry-level luxury sedan that standardizes proximity ''smart key'' technology across its production run. It utilizes the NXP Hitag 3 (ID47) or AES (ID8A) security platforms depending on the specific model year. Proximity programming is consistent with the Honda Civic platform and is well-supported by Autel and Xhorse tools. If the dashboard doesn''t wake up during programming, try holding the key directly against the Start/Stop button.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|Integra', 'The Acura Integra is a legendary sport compact that returned to the lineup in 2023 with modern security features. While vintage models often lacked transponders, the newest generation uses a high-security encrypted proximity system. Programming the 2023+ models requires modern tools with updated Honda/Acura security protocols and often an active internet connection. For classic models, the mechanical ignition is prone to ''tumbler collapse,'' so always check the mechanical operation first.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|Legend', 'The Acura Legend was Acura''s flagship luxury sedan in the 1990s and generally preceded the widespread use of transponders. Most models use a high-security ''sidewinder'' (laser-cut) key but do not have an immobilizer chip in the early years. Cutting keys for these requires a dedicated high-security cutter and an accurate code or lishi decoding. Note that the trunk lock often has more wafers than the door, making it the better choice for decoding a lost key.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|MDX', 'The Acura MDX is a popular three-row luxury SUV that has evolved through multiple security generations from ID48 to modern proximity AES. Newer models utilize a rolling-code proximity system that is generally very stable but sensitive to low battery voltage. Most professional tools can perform ''All Keys Lost'' through the OBDII port without needing an EEPROM pull. On 2022+ models, ensure you have the correct frequency smart key as several variants look identical but are incompatible.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|NSX', 'The Acura NSX is a high-performance supercar with security systems that are significantly more complex than standard Acura models. Early models used unique transponder chips, while the hybrid generation uses a highly protected proximity architecture. Programming often requires official Acura i-HDS or very high-end aftermarket tools with specific supercar software modules. Always use a battery maintainer as the NSX has complex electronics that can be sensitive to voltage fluctuations during programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|RDX', 'The Acura RDX is a compact luxury crossover that transitioned to full proximity systems early in its second generation. It uses the Honda security architecture, moving from ID46 to Hitag 3 and newer encrypted protocols. Proximity keys are easily added via standard OBDII procedures on most professional locksmith platforms. For newer models, the ''Smart System'' can occasionally lock out if too many failed attempts occur, so follow the on-screen prompts carefully.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|RL', 'The Acura RL was a flagship sedan and one of the first to implement the ''Advanced Smart Key'' system with a twist-knob ignition. This specific system uses a unique proximity protocol that can be finicky compared to the newer push-button start systems. You often need to program the mechanical ''emergency'' key transponder first before the proximity functions will initialize. Check the door handle antennas frequently, as moisture ingress can cause the proximity system to fail independently of the programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|RLX', 'The Acura RLX is a premium luxury sedan that utilizes Acura''s most advanced push-button start proximity systems. It typically uses the Hitag 3 or newer security platform and is well-covered by major programming tools. The process is usually quick, requiring only the presence of a valid or new smart key in the cabin. If programming fails, check for aftermarket remote starts or ''save-data'' modules which can block the OBDII communication path.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|RSX', 'The Acura RSX is a sporty compact coupe that utilizes the Megamos ID48 transponder system throughout its production run. This is one of the easiest Acuras to program, as the ID48 system is very standard across the Honda/Acura line of that era. Most technicians can complete a key addition or ''All Keys Lost'' in under 5 minutes using any basic OBDII programmer. Be aware that the ignition locks are known to wear out, often requiring the replacement of the lock cylinder itself.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|SLX', 'The Acura SLX was a rebadged Isuzu Trooper and features Isuzu''s specific security and mechanical architecture rather than Acura''s. These vehicles often lack a transponder system entirely or use an early Isuzu-specific transponder module. Programming, if applicable, requires selecting Isuzu software rather than Acura to communicate with the immobilizer. Mechanically, the keys are standard double-sided cuts and are relatively simple to decode and duplicate.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|TL', 'The Acura TL is a mainstay of the luxury sedan market with security ranging from early Megamos transponders to modern proximity keys. Models from 2004-2008 use the Philips ID46 chip, while 2009+ models transitioned to different proximity or high-security transponder variants. Most TL keys can be programmed via OBDII in minutes, though some proximity models require a specific ''bypass'' sequence for the steering lock. Always verify the FCC ID on the remote to ensure the internal frequency matches the vehicle''s receiver.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|TLX', 'The Acura TLX is a modern sport sedan that utilizes a sophisticated proximity-based security architecture. It uses the Hitag 3 or newer AES security platforms, consistent with luxury Honda vehicles of the same era. Programming is generally very efficient with tools like the IM608 or Lonsdor K518, typically taking less than 10 minutes. For the 2021+ ''Type S'' and newer models, ensure your tool is updated to the latest Acura software to handle the newer encryption layers.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|TSX', 'The Acura TSX is a popular entry-level luxury sedan known for its reliability and straightforward security systems. It evolved from using Philips ID46 transponder keys to various proximity systems in later years. The OBDII programming process is very consistent and has a high success rate across all major locksmith tool platforms. If you encounter a ''security light flashing'' after programming, perform a simple battery reset to clear the immobilizer buffer.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|Vigor', 'The Acura Vigor was an early 1990s luxury sedan that used traditional mechanical keys without any transponder security. It features high-security ''sidewinder'' (laser-cut) keys that require specialized cutting equipment but no electronic programming. Decoding can be done via the door lock, but be prepared for a 10-wafer system that requires precision. Since there is no immobilizer, once the key is cut mechanically, the vehicle will start immediately.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Acura|ZDX', 'The Acura ZDX is a luxury crossover that uses the same proximity security architecture as the contemporary MDX and TL models. It utilizes Hitag-based proximity keys that are easily programmed through the OBDII port on most professional systems. The process is standard for Acura, usually involving a few ''IG-ON'' cycles and proximity recognition steps. Ensure the vehicle''s battery is fully charged, as the ZDX has a high electronic draw that can interrupt the programming sequence.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Alfa Romeo|4C Coupe', 'The Alfa Romeo 4C is a lightweight sports car that uses a security architecture derived from specialized Fiat and Chrysler platforms. It typically uses a Megamos ID48 or similar encrypted transponder system depending on the market and production year. Programming can be complex and often requires tools that support ''Fiat/Chrysler'' protocols or a specialized pre-coding process. Because of the carbon fiber monocoque, antenna range can occasionally be limited, so place the key precisely where instructed.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Alfa Romeo|4C Spider', 'The Alfa Romeo 4C Spider shares the same security architecture as the Coupe, utilizing a Fiat-based transponder system. It often requires obtaining a 5-digit PIN code from the dealer or extracting it directly from the BCM using advanced tools. Programming is generally a two-step process: pre-coding the transponder for the specific vehicle and then initializing it via OBDII. Ensure you are using high-quality aftermarket or OEM keys, as cheap clones often fail to handshake with the sensitive Italian security modules.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Alfa Romeo|Giulia', 'The Alfa Romeo Giulia is a modern luxury sedan that utilizes a sophisticated security system with a mandatory Security Gateway Module (SGW) on 2018+ models. It uses proximity keys that are closely related to the newer Jeep and Chrysler architectures. Programming requires an SGW bypass cable or a tool with authorized FCA server access to communicate with the vehicle. Once the gateway is bypassed, adding proximity keys is relatively straightforward but requires precise timing for the ignition cycles.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Alfa Romeo|Giulietta Coupe', 'The Alfa Romeo Giulietta is an Italian-market mainstay that utilizes the Fiat-based ''Code 2'' transponder architecture. It uses Megamos ID48 transponder chips that must be pre-coded with specific vehicle data (CS) before they can be programmed via OBDII. This usually requires a tool like the Tango or specialized Fiat diagnostic software to read the BCM first. Always check for a ''Check Engine'' light after programming, as invalid key attempts can occasionally trigger generic ECU faults on these models.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Alfa Romeo|MiTo', 'The Alfa Romeo MiTo is a compact hatchback that shares its security platform with the Fiat Grande Punto. It utilizes the Fiat Code 2 system with ID48 transponders that require pre-generation from the BCM''s EEPROM data. Most professional tools can now perform this ''All Keys Lost'' procedure through the OBDII port by reading the BCM and then prepping the key in one flow. Be aware that the BCM on these models is often located in the passenger footwell and can be prone to water damage.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Alfa Romeo|Stelvio', 'The Alfa Romeo Stelvio is a performance SUV that uses the same modern FCA-derived security architecture as the Giulia. On 2018 and newer models, the Security Gateway Module (SGW) must be bypassed to allow any OBDII programming. It uses proximity keys that are very standard for the FCA group but require a specific pre-authorization step. If the proximity functions work but the engine won''t start, check that the transponder portion was successfully synced to the central BCM.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('AMC|Alliance', 'The AMC Alliance was a product of the AMC/Renault partnership and uses early Renault mechanical key systems. These vehicles do not have any transponder or electronic security, relying entirely on a traditional metal key for operation. Keys are typically simple single-sided or double-sided cuts that can be duplicated easily by any local locksmith. Because of the French design influence, the locks can be somewhat fragile, so use care when decoding them manually.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('AMC|Eagle', 'The AMC Eagle was a pioneering all-wheel-drive vehicle that utilized standard Chrysler mechanical ignition and door locks of its era. There is no electronic transponder or immobilizer system present in any of the AMC Eagle models. The keys are standard Chrysler M-series or similar cuts that are widely available and simple to duplicate. Most locksmiths can create a key for these from scratch using basic impressioning or by pulling a door lock for decoding.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('AMC|Encore', 'The AMC Encore was a compact car based on Renault engineering that utilized strictly mechanical security for its entire run. No transponder or electronic anti-theft systems were used, making the locksmith''s job purely mechanical. Keys are standard Renault blanks and can be cut on any traditional key machine with high accuracy. Like other Renault-based AMC models, the ignition cylinder is the most common failure point and may require replacement rather than just a new key.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|100', 'The Audi 100 was a classic executive sedan that utilized early mechanical key systems with high-security laser-cut profiles. Most models from the early 90s do not have a transponder system, while the very last production years may feature basic Megamos ID13 fixed-code chips. Programming for transponder-equipped models is simple if the PIN is known, though most locksmiths can clone these chips easily. Mechanically, the locks are robust but require specialized laser-cutting equipment for precision replication.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|80', 'The Audi 80 served as the predecessor to the A4 and features high-security mechanical locks with early-generation immobilizer technology. Transponder models typically use Megamos ID13 chips which are easily cloneable or programmable via OBDII with the correct PIN. For ''All Keys Lost'' scenarios, the PIN can often be extracted from the immobilizer box or instrument cluster using professional VAG tools. Always check the trunk lock for decoding, as it often suffers less wear than the driver''s door lock.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|90', 'The Audi 90 was a more upscale version of the Audi 80, sharing the same mechanical and electronic security architecture. It uses laser-cut keys and Megamos transponders in its later production years, requiring high-security cutting and basic transponder programming. Most professional locksmith tools like the Autel IM608 handle these easily via the VAG software module. Note that the ignition switch itself is a common failure point and may need replacement if the key turns roughly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A3', 'The Audi A3 is a compact premium vehicle that spans multiple security generations, from Megamos ID48 to modern MQB architectures. Newer MQB-based models (2014+) require advanced tools and often server-side calculation for ''All Keys Lost'' or even adding a spare. Older models with ID48 chips are well-supported via OBDII, though PIN extraction from the cluster or ECU is usually required. For the latest MQB models, always verify tool compatibility as the security protocols are frequently updated by VAG.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A4', 'The Audi A4 is a core part of the Audi lineup, evolving from early ID48 transponders to the B8/B9 BCM2 and modern MQB security systems. B8 models (2009-2016) use the BCM2 system where keys are programmed via OBDII, though some ''Year 2013-2015'' models require dealer-online access for sync. B9 models (2017+) utilize the most advanced encryption, often requiring specialized bypasses or authorized server tokens. Always use high-quality OEM or certified aftermarket smart keys to ensure reliable remote and proximity functionality.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A4 ALLROAD', 'The Audi A4 Allroad utilizes the same security and BCM2/MQB architectures as the standard A4 sedan and Avant models. Programming procedures are identical to the A4, typically requiring PIN extraction and key initialization through the OBDII port. For newer generations, the 5th Gen Immobilizer or MQB systems require advanced software and connectivity. Be aware that the proximity antenna range can be sensitive, so ensure the key is placed in the designated ''Emergency'' slot if the car doesn''t detect it initially.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A5', 'The Audi A5 is a stylish coupe that shares its BCM2 and MQB security platforms with the contemporary A4. Most A5 models use proximity smart keys that require a multi-step programming process involving the reading of BCM2 data. Major professional platforms like Autel, Lonsdor, and Xhorse provide good coverage for most years, though 2017+ models are more restrictive. If the remote functions don''t work after programming the transponder, ensure the ''Remote Learning'' routine was fully completed in the software.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A5 Cabriolet', 'The Audi A5 Cabriolet features the same security architecture as its coupe counterpart, with specific considerations for the proximity system near the convertible top modules. Security ranges from BCM2 proximity keys to modern MQB encryption depending on the generation. Programming is well-supported by high-end locksmith tools, though ''All Keys Lost'' on newer models can be a significant technical challenge. Keep the battery on a charger during the process, as the A5 Cabriolet has sophisticated electronics that drain power quickly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A6', 'The Audi A6 is a mid-size executive sedan that has transitioned from early ID48 and KESSY systems to the robust BCM2 and modern MQB platforms. Older C6 models with KESSY require specialized tools to read the EZS/Kessy module for programming. C7 and C8 models (2012+) use BCM2 or MQB security, requiring advanced data extraction and often server authorization for key learning. Note that for BCM2 models, you must often read the BCM2 data first to prepare a ''Dealer Key'' before it can be learned to the car.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A6 ALLROAD', 'The Audi A6 Allroad shares the same technical and security infrastructure as the A6 Avant, featuring BCM2 or MQB-based immobilizer systems. Programming keys for these vehicles requires advanced VAG-specific software capable of reading encrypted data from the BCM or ECU. The process for proximity keys is well-defined in tools like the IM608 but requires a steady internet connection for some years. In ''All Keys Lost'' situations, be prepared for a longer extraction time compared to more basic Audi models.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A7', 'The Audi A7 utilizes Audi''s most advanced security platforms, primarily the BCM2 and later MQB systems, consistent with the A6 and A8. High-security proximity keys are standard, requiring a sophisticated handshake between the key and several modules including the BCM and ELV. Programming typically requires high-end tools with ''Expert'' VAG modules and occasionally an online connection to the VAG server for newer versions. Always verify if the vehicle has the ''Advanced Key'' (Keyless Go) option, as it requires a specific smart key variant.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|A8', 'As Audi''s flagship, the A8 features the earliest and most complex implementations of Audi''s security tech, including the 4th and 5th Gen Immobilizer systems. Programming older D3 models requires reading the KESSY module, while D4 and D5 models utilize the BCM2 or MQB architectures. This level of security often demands top-tier equipment such as VVDI2 or IM608 with specific Audi authorization. For ''All Keys Lost'' on newer A8s, the process is highly technical and should only be attempted by experienced locksmiths with the proper backup power.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|Q3', 'The Audi Q3 is a compact SUV that primarily utilizes either the 4th Gen Immobilizer (PQ35) or the newer MQB security platform. PQ35 models are relatively easy to program using standard VAG procedures and common locksmith tools. MQB models (approximately 2015+) require significantly more advanced tools for data extraction and key preparation. If your tool fails to read the cluster data on an MQB model, you may need to use a specialized gateway bypass or an online programming service.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|Q5', 'The Audi Q5 is a popular luxury crossover that utilized the BCM2 security platform for many years before moving to MQB. Proximity smart keys are the norm, and programming them involves reading the BCM2 data and preparing a dealer key. Most professional tools offer reliable OBDII coverage for the first and early second-generation models. For ''All Keys Lost'' on newer Q5s, ensure you have the correct key frequency (315MHz vs 433MHz) based on the vehicle''s market and trim.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|Q7', 'The Audi Q7 is a full-size luxury SUV that shifted from early KESSY-based security to the BCM2 and current MQB architectures. Programming for the first generation (2007-2015) usually requires reading the EZS or KESSY module data. Second-generation models (2016+) are MQB-based and require the latest VAG security protocols and often an online server connection. Given the high complexity of the Q7''s electronics, always perform a full system scan before and after key programming to ensure no modules were desynced.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|Q8', 'The Audi Q8 features Audi''s most modern and restrictive security architecture, strictly utilizing the latest MQB and 5th Gen Immobilizer protocols. Keys are proximity-based and require advanced tools with specific ''2019+'' VAG software updates for successful programming. Many operations for the Q8 currently require an online connection to the VAG data backend or a specialized token service. Use only original OEM keys for this model to avoid ''Key Not Recognized'' errors which are common with low-quality aftermarket chips.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|R8', 'The Audi R8 is a mid-engine supercar that surprisingly shares much of its security DNA with the contemporary Lamborghini platforms. It uses advanced transponder and proximity systems that require high-end tools with specific supercar software modules. Programming is often a multi-stage process that includes reading the ECU or BCM and carefully initializing the new key. Because of the limited production numbers, software support can be more niche, so verify your tool''s specific R8 coverage before arriving at the job.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|RS4', 'The Audi RS4 high-performance model utilizes the same security architecture as its A4/S4 counterparts, typically following the BCM2 or MQB platforms. Special care is needed as these limited-production models sometimes feature unique interior trims that can make accessing the BCM or cluster more difficult. Programming follows the standard VAG 4th or 5th Gen Immobilizer flow using professional-grade tools. Always verify the chassis type (B7, B8, B9) to ensure you are using the correct transponder chip or proximity key variant.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|S3', 'The Audi S3 shares its MQB or PQ35 security platform with the standard A3, requiring similar tools and procedures for key programming. Newer S3 models are almost exclusively MQB, necessitating advanced data extraction and dealer-key preparation steps. OBDII programming is generally successful for adding a spare, while ''All Keys Lost'' is more complex on the newer encrypted clusters. Ensure you have a stable internet connection if your tool requires server-side calculations for the MQB immobilizer data.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|S4', 'The Audi S4 utilizes the same BCM2 and MQB security architectures as the A4 sedan, with most modern versions using proximity smart keys. Programming is well-supported by tools like the IM608 and VVDI2, typically involving a read of the BCM data followed by a key learning cycle. For models with the ''Safe'' lock system, ensuring the proximity key is correctly ''Dealer Key'' prepared is critical for success. If the programming hangs, try a hard battery reset and ensure all doors are closed during the sequence.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|S5', 'The Audi S5 shares the BCM2 and MQB platforms with the A5, utilizing high-security proximity smart keys for most of its production. Key programming is a standard VAG procedure but requires professional tools capable of handling 5th Gen or MQB security layers. ''All Keys Lost'' is possible via OBDII for many years but becomes significantly more difficult for 2017+ models using the newest encryption. As with all high-trim Audis, low battery voltage is the most common cause of programming failure, so use a booster or tender.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|S6', 'The Audi S6 features themid-to-high level security architectures found in the A6, including BCM2 and the latest MQB protocols. For proximity models, the BCM2 data must usually be extracted via OBDII or ''on-bench'' if OBDI is blocked to prepare a new key. Success rates are high with professional-grade VAG equipment, provided the technician follows the multi-step dealer-key prep process accurately. Due to the high number of modules on the S6, always check for any existing communication faults before starting the programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|S7', 'The Audi S7 utilizes a sophisticated BCM2 and MQB security platform identical to the A7 and A6 performance models. Proximity smart keys require a multi-stage programming flow involving PIN/CS extraction and dealer key generation. Most modern professional tools cover this model well, but 2018+ variants may require an online server token for full access. Always verify the key''s internal frequency (315MHz for US, 433MHz for EU) before attempting to program, as they are not cross-compatible.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|S8', 'The Audi S8 features Audi''s elite-tier security infrastructure, consistent with the A8 flagship sedan. It uses the BCM2 or 5th Gen Immobilizer MQB systems which are highly resistant to unauthorized programming. Technicians must use top-tier equipment and often follow a specialized ''Expert Mode'' sequence to successfully add or replace keys. Given the value and complexity of the S8, avoid using unverified aftermarket keys, as they frequently cause immobilizer lock-out or ''Key Not Recognized'' warnings.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Audi|TT', 'The Audi TT has evolved from basic Megamos ID48 systems in the first generation to the current MQB security architecture in the third generation. First-gen (8N) models are very simple to program via OBDII once the 4-digit PIN is obtained. Second-gen (8J) and third-gen (8S) models require more advanced tools and MQB-specific software modules for key learning. For ''All Keys Lost'' on the newest TTs, expect to perform a cluster or BCM data pull which requires specialized equipment and training.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|1-Series M', 'The BMW 1-Series M is a rare performance coupe that utilizes BMW''s CAS3+ security platform. Programming requires reading the CAS data via OBDII or on-bench to decrypt the ISN and prepare a new dealer key. While adding a key is straightforward with professional tools like VVDI2 or IM608, ''All Keys Lost'' requires more advanced data recovery. Note that the CAS system is sensitive to voltage dips, so always use a stable power supply during the programming process.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|2-Series', 'The BMW 2-Series primarily uses the FEM (Front Electronic Module) or BDC (Body Domain Controller) security architectures. Programming keys for these vehicles involves a complex process of reading the module data, often requiring the module to be initialized on-bench first for some years. Success rates are high with modern locksmith platforms, but 2018+ models with newer firmware can be significantly more restrictive. Always verify if the vehicle has the ''Comfort Access'' option, as it requires a specific proximity key variant for full functionality.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|3-Series', 'The BMW 3-Series is a high-volume model that has transitioned through EWS, CAS, FEM, and BDC security generations. Early E-Series models with CAS systems are relatively easy to program, while newer F-Series and G-Series models use the FEM/BDC architecture which is much more secure. For BDC models, the process usually involves reading the 8-pin EEPROM to extract the coding data before a key can be learned via OBDII. Pro tip: Always check for aftermarket ''emulator'' devices which are common on these models and can interfere with the security handshake.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|4-Series', 'The BMW 4-Series utilizes the FEM/BDC security platform, consistent with the contemporary 3-Series models. Programming typically requires mapping the module and preparing a dealer key using specialized locksmith equipment like the Lonsdor K518 or Xhorse VVDI BMW. For models with the ''Silver/Black'' proximity keys, ensure you have the correct frequency (315MHz vs 434MHz) as they are not interchangeable. In cases of ''All Keys Lost,'' it is often necessary to pull the FEM/BDC module for a more reliable data read.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|5-Series', 'The BMW 5-Series evolved from CAS systems in E-Series to CAS4/CAS4+ and modern BDC architectures in the G-Series. CAS4+ models (approximately 2011-2016) are notable for their encryption, requiring the extraction of the ISN from the ECU for ''All Keys Lost'' scenarios. Current G-Series models using BDC are highly secure and often require authorized server access or very advanced decryption tools. Always perform a full system backup before modifying any module data on a 5-Series to prevent bricking the central gateway.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|6-Series', 'The BMW 6-Series shares its CAS and BDC security architecture with the contemporary 5-Series and 7-Series models. Programming focus is on reading the CAS4 or BDC module data to generate a valid dealer key that the vehicle will accept. Most professional BMW-specific locksmith tools provide good coverage, though ''Comfort Access'' keys require additional initialization steps. Be careful with the battery during programming, as the 6-Series has a high number of control units that remain active, draining power quickly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|7-Series', 'As BMW''s flagship, the 7-Series features the most complex security implementations, including early CAS and the latest BDC/G-Series architectures. Programming for these vehicles often requires reading and writing to the BDC module or the N63/S63 engine computers to sync the immobilizer data. This is a high-skill job that demands top-tier equipment like the Autohex or BMW Explorer for reliable results. Note that the 7-Series frequently uses unique key fobs with integrated screens which are significantly more expensive and technical to program.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|8-Series', 'The modern BMW 8-Series utilizes the latest G-Series BDC security architecture, featuring very high levels of encryption and protected communication paths. Key programming typically requires advanced tools with specific ''G-Series'' software and often involves a multi-stage authorization process. Most operations for this model currently require online connectivity to verify security certificates or specialized on-bench decryption. Use only original OEM keys to ensure all luxury features, including remote parking and digital key functions, operate correctly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|M3', 'The BMW M3 high-performance model uses the security platform of its 3-Series base, ranging from CAS to modern BDC systems. Because M-models often have high-security ECU variants (S-series engines), extracting the ISN for ''All Keys Lost'' can be more difficult than on standard models. Programming is well-supported by high-end BMW tools, but use caution when reading module data on these premium models. Always check the ''Emergency Key'' slot location, as M-spec interiors occasionally have different trim panels covering the antenna loop.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|M4', 'The BMW M4 utilizes the FEM/BDC security architecture found in the 4-Series, with specific encryption for the high-performance S55 or S58 engine controllers. Adding a key involves reading the FEM/BDC module andPreparing a new smart key that matches the vehicle''s coding. ''All Keys Lost'' is a technical process that often requires on-bench work to extract the necessary security secret (ISN). Ensure your programming tool is fully updated to the latest BMW software to handle the specific M-model communication protocols.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|M5', 'The BMW M5 features the most advanced versions of the CAS4+ or BDC security systems, matching the 5-Series but with higher security EGS/ECU pairings. Programming requires top-tier BMW-specialized equipment and a deep understanding of BMW''s ISN/secret-key architecture. For modern F90 M5 models, expect a highly secure BDC system that may requiring individual module authorization for key learning. pro tip: If the key isn''t recognized, check for interference from carbon fiber interior trim which can block the low-frequency proximity antennas.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|M6', 'The BMW M6 shares its CAS4+ or BDC security infrastructure with the 6-Series and M5, requiring similar high-end tools for key programming. Success depends on accurately reading the CAS or BDC data to generate a dealer-prepped key that the car''s immobilizer will trust. This model is known for its complex electronics, so a dedicated battery maintainer is essential during any OBDII or on-bench programming. For ''All Keys Lost,'' you must often sync the new key with the high-performance DME (Digital Motor Electronics) to enable the starter.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|X1', 'The BMW X1 has evolved from CAS3+ systems in the first generation to the newer BDC/FEM architectures in the second and third generations. First-generation (E84) models are easily handled via OBDII with tools like the VVDI2 or IM608. Second-generation (F48) models use the BDC system, which requires a more involved process of reading and prepping the module. Always verify if the car has the ''Silver/Round'' key or the newer ''Triangle'' style, as they represent different security platforms within the same model year.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|X2', 'The BMW X2 is built on the F48 platform and utilizes the BDC (Body Domain Controller) security architecture for all its models. Key programming involves reading the BDC''s internal data, which often requires the technician to put the module into ''Programming Mode'' first. While adding a spare key is consistent across most BMW-specialized tools, ''All Keys Lost'' remains a more technical challenge involving ISN extraction. Ensure you have the correct key frequency, as BMW uses several variants that are visually identical but electronically incompatible.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|X3', 'The BMW X3 transitioned from CAS3 systems to CAS4 and the current BDC architecture across its three generations. E83 models use simple transponders, while F25 and G01 models use much more advanced CAS4+ and BDC proximity keys. Programming for the G-Series (2018+) is particularly secure and may require an online connection or very advanced decryption software. For E-Series models, be aware that the GM-style door locks are prone to failure and may need mechanical attention to allow proper decoding.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|X4', 'The BMW X4 shares its mechanical and security DNA with the X3, utilizing the same CAS4 and BDC platforms. Programming for most F-Series models (F26) is well-supported through the OBDII port once the CAS4+ data is extracted. For G-Series models (G02), the security is significantly tighter, often requiring the use of high-end BMW-specific locksmith platforms. pro tip: If the car has ''Comfort Access,'' the key must be a specific proximity-enabled version; many cheaper aftermarket keys only support ''Insert and Start'' functionality.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|X5', 'The BMW X5 is a pioneer of BMW SUV security, moving from EWS to CAS3, CAS4, and the modern G-Series BDC platform. Each generation represented a jump in security; CAS3 models are simple, while CAS4+ and BDC models require advanced ISN reading from the engine ECU. For ''All Keys Lost'' on modern X5s, you must often access the BDC and the DME simultaneously to sync the immobilizer chain. Always use a high-amp battery charger, as the X5''s numerous modules can quickly draw the battery down during the programming cycle.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|X6', 'The BMW X6 uses the same advanced CAS and BDC security architectures as the contemporary X5 and 5-Series models. Programming focus is on reading the CAS4+ or BDC data to prepare a dealer-equivalent key that the vehicle will accept. While adding keys is common via OBDII with professional tools, the process involves multiple steps to confirm the security secret (ISN). On newer G-Series models, expect highly encrypted BDC modules that may require specialized decryption or authorized server-side tokens for key learning.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|Z3', 'The BMW Z3 utilizes the early EWS2 or EWS3 security platform, featuring a simple transponder chip and mechanical key. Key programming for these models is best done ''on-bench'' by reading the EWS module directly, though some early OBDII clones are possible. This is one of the most straightforward BMWs for a locksmith, as the EWS logic is well-understood and well-documented. Mechanically, the keys are standard BMW 2-track or early 4-track cuts which are simple to replicate with any basic high-security cutter.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|Z4', 'The BMW Z4 evolved from CAS units in the E85/E86 to CAS3+ in the E89 and the latest BDC architecture in the G29. E-Series Z4 models are easily programmed through the OBDII port using most professional locksmith equipment. The newest G-Series Z4 (which shares its platform with the Toyota Supra) uses a highly secure BDC system that requires advanced decryption tools. For the newer models, it is critical to use high-quality proximity keys to ensure the complex ''Comfort Access'' features work flawlessly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|i3', 'The BMW i3 electric vehicle utilizes the BDC (Body Domain Controller) security architecture for all its production years. Programing keys involves reading the BDC data, which is a highly technical process requiring specialized BMW-capable locksmith tools. Because it is an EV, the 12V battery is small and can be easily drained during programming, so always use a stable external power source. Proximity keys for the i3 are specific to this model, so verify you have the correct FCC ID before starting the job.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('BMW|i8', 'The BMW i8 hybrid supercar utilizes the CAS4+ or BDC security platform, featuring many unique performance-based encryption layers. Programming typically requires high-end tools with professional BMW software modules and often an on-bench read of the security module. Because of the i8''s specialized build, standard locksmith tools may have gaps in coverage, so always verify your tool''s specific i8 chassis. Use only genuine OEM smart keys to ensure the remote functions and vehicle status displays on the key fob operate correctly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Buick|Enclave', 'The Buick Enclave is a large luxury crossover that transitioned from the GM ''Circle Plus'' transponder system to advanced proximity keys. It utilizes the GM Global-A or Global-B platforms depending on the production year. Programming for most models is easily accomplished through the OBDII port using the ''Add Key'' or ''All Keys Lost'' routines. Pro tip: If the proximity key is not recognized, placed it in the center console pocket (induction coil location) to establish a firm communication link.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Buick|Encore', 'The Buick Encore is a subcompact luxury SUV that uses the GM Global-A security architecture, featuring both flip-keys and proximity smart keys. It typically uses the Philips ID46 or Hitag 3 (ID47) transponder chips which are widely supported by all major locksmith tools. Programming is usually a 10-12 minute process, requiring the ignition to remain on for a ''security wait'' period on some trim levels. Always verify the button configuration on the remote to ensure the remote start and trunk functions operate as intended.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Buick|LaCrosse', 'The Buick LaCrosse features a security system that evolved from standard PK3+ transponder keys to high-security proximity systems. It utilizes the GM Global-A platform, and newer models (2017+) may feature the Global-B architecture which requires CAN-FD capable tools. Most professional programmers can handle this vehicle in under 15 minutes through the standard OBDII routine. Watch for the ''Service Theft Deterrent'' message on the dashboard, which often indicates a failed transponder read rather than a hardware fault.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Buick|Regal', 'The Buick Regal, often based on Opel engineering, utilizes a robust GM Global-A security system throughout its modern run. It uses high-security laser-cut keys and proximity smart keys that are easily programmable using standard GM software modules. The process is generally very reliable, but ensure the battery is fully charged as the BCM can be sensitive during the security handshake. Note that for ''All Keys Lost'', some models may require a 12-minute waiting period per key during the learn sequence.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Buick|Verano', 'The Buick Verano uses the GM Global-A security platform, featuring many components shared with the Chevrolet Cruze. It utilizes a high-security flip-key or proximity smart key with an ID46 or Hitag 3 transponder. Programming is straightforward via OBDII, typically taking about 10 minutes to complete the security cycle. pro tip: If you encounter a ''Key Not Initialized'' error, perform a full module scan to ensure the Immobilizer and BCM are communicating correctly before retrying.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|ATS', 'The Cadillac ATS is a luxury sport sedan that utilizes the GM Global-A proximity security architecture. It uses Hitag-based smart keys that are easily programmed through the OBDII port on most professional systems. The process is standard for Cadillac, usually involving placing the key in the specific transmitter pocket located in the center console or armrest. For newer models, ensure your tool is updated to handle the latest GM encryption layers to avoid communication failures.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|CT4', 'The Cadillac CT4 utilizes the modern GM Global-B architecture, which is significantly more secure than previous generations. Programming requires tools that support CAN-FD communication and often an active connection to GM''s security servers for authorization. Adding a key is typically a structured process that must be followed exactly to avoid locking the Security Gateway. Always use original OEM smart keys for Global-B vehicles to ensure all advanced proximity and remote features operate flawlessly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|CT5', 'The Cadillac CT5 also operates on the GM Global-B platform, featuring high-level encryption and a Security Gateway Module. A CAN-FD adapter and authorized software are mandatory for any OBDII key programming on this model. The learning process involves multiple authentication steps and is designed to resist unauthorized access. Because of the complexity, ensure the vehicle''s battery voltage is strictly maintained throughout the programming procedure to prevent data corruption.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|CTS', 'The Cadillac CTS evolved from early transponder systems to the widely used Global-A proximity architecture. Most models use Hitag 3 or ID46 transponders that are easily programmed via OBDII in about 12 minutes. The proximity transmitter pocket is usually found in the center console; placing the key there is essential for the vehicle to recognize it during the learn phase. Check the door handle antennas frequently, as moisture ingress can cause the proximity system to fail independently of the programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|DTS', 'The Cadillac DTS uses the GM ''Circle Plus'' transponder system (PK3+) and traditional single-sided or double-sided keys. This is a very straightforward system for locksmiths, with most tools completing the programming in under 10 minutes via OBDII. The transponder chip is usually an ID46 (Philips) or similar variant depending on the specific year. Be aware that the ignition cylinders are prone to mechanical wear, so always test the mechanical operation before final programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|Escalade', 'The Cadillac Escalade is a high-theft target and features robust security ranging from early PK3+ to modern Global-B proximity systems. Newer models (2021+) require CAN-FD adapters and often online server authorization for any key learning activities. Programming for older generations is very consistent using standard professional GM software modules. pro tip: In ''All Keys Lost'' scenarios on newer models, the process can take up to 30 minutes, so verify you have the correct FCC ID smart key before starting.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|SRX', 'The Cadillac SRX utilizes the GM Global-A security platform, featuring proximity smart keys across most of its production years. Programming is easily accomplished through the OBDII port using tools like the IM608 or Lonsdor K518. The transmitter pocket is located in the center console or on the steering column, depending on the year. Ensure the battery is healthy, as the SRX''s complex electronics can cause the BCM to drop communication if the voltage dips during the write process.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|XT4', 'The Cadillac XT4 uses the GM Global-B security architecture, necessitating the use of CAN-FD hardware for all key programming. It features highly encrypted proximity keys that must be authorized through the Security Gateway Module. Success rates are high with updated professional tools, but the process is more time-consuming than on older Global-A models. For ''All Keys Lost,'' many technicians prefer using an online AC-Delco service to ensure the BCM security identifiers are correctly calculated.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|XT5', 'The Cadillac XT5 primarily utilizes the GM Global-A proximity system, with later models transitioning toward Global-B. Proximity key programming is a standard 12-minute GM process that is well-supported by all major locksmith tool brands. If the key is not detected during programming, check the transmitter pocket in the center console for any metallic debris or coins that could interfere with the signal. Note that for 2020+ models, you may need a specialized bypass or authorized tool to communicate with the BCM.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Cadillac|XTS', 'The Cadillac XTS uses the GM Global-A proximity security platform, featuring high-precision proximity sensors and encrypted transponders. Programming is usually quick and reliable through the OBDII port, typically requiring the key to be placed in the center console pocket. Watch for ''Key Not Detected'' errors which can often be solved by replacing the battery in the key fob. For ''All Keys Lost'', follow the standard GM 12-minute learn sequence, ensuring the vehicle is not in ''Economy Mode'' during the process.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Astrou', 'The Chevrolet Astro utilizes the standard early GM Passlock II security system, which relies on a resistor-based key or simple transponder. This system is very straightforward for locksmiths, with most tools supporting clear and relearn procedures in under 10 minutes. The mechanical keys are standard GM 6-cut or 10-cut profiles that are easily duplicated with any mechanical key machine. pro tip: If the ''Security'' light is flashing, check for broken wires at the base of the ignition cylinder, which is a common failure point on the Astro.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Avalanche', 'The Chevrolet Avalanche uses the GM ''Circle Plus'' (PK3+) transponder system, consistent with the Silverado and Suburban models of its era. This system uses a Philips ID46 transponder chip and is easily programmed via the OBDII port on almost any locksmith tool. The mechanical keys are standard high-security or traditional cuts depending on the year, and are generally robust against wear. Most technicians can complete a key addition or ''All Keys Lost'' in approximately 10 minutes through the standard GM routine.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Aveo', 'The Chevrolet Aveo, a rebadged Daewoo, utilizes a unique transponder system that is different from standard GM architecture. It typically uses an ID48 Megamos chip or a Daewoo-specific transponder module depending on the market and production year. Programming can be finicky and often requires tools with specific Daewoo/Aveo software rather than the standard Chevrolet modules. Watch for the ''Immobilizer Connection'' faults, which are common on these models due to poor grounding in the steering column.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Blazer', 'The Chevrolet Blazer spans multiple generations, from early Passlock systems to the modern Global-A proximity platform. Newer Blazer models (2019+) use proximity smart keys that are easily programmed through the OBDII port in a standard 12-minute GM learn cycle. For older S-10 based Blazers, the Passlock II system can often be bypassed or reset using basic diagnostic equipment. pro tip: On modern proximity models, the transmitter pocket is usually in the center console; ensure any RFID-blocking items are removed during programming.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Camaro', 'The Chevrolet Camaro features security ranging from early VATS (resistor keys) to high-security flip-keys and proximity smart systems. Modern Camaros (since 2010) utilize the GM Global-A platform, which is well-supported by professional locksmith tools and takes about 10-12 minutes to program. For ''All Keys Lost'' on newer proximity models, ensure you have the correct frequency smart key as several variants look identical but are incompatible. Older VATS models require a specialized VATS interrogator or a resistance measurement to create a matching key.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Colorado', 'The Chevrolet Colorado utilizes the GM ''Circle Plus'' transponder system or the modern Global-A platform depending on the generation. It uses traditional transponder keys with ID46 chips or high-security flip-keys that are easily programmed via OBDII. Most locksmiths can perform a key addition or ''All Keys Lost'' through a standard 10-minute routine. Note that 2023+ models move to the Global-B architecture, requiring CAN-FD hardware and potentially authorized server access for security operations.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Corvette', 'The Chevrolet Corvette has always featured advanced security, from VATS to the first-ever proximity-only systems in the C6/C7 generation. C6-C8 models use proximity smart keys that require a specialized learn sequence, often involving the door key or specific button combinations inside the cabin. Programming success depends on a very stable battery voltage, so a tender or booster is strongly recommended. For C8 models, the Global-B architecture is present, necessitating CAN-FD tools and professional-grade security authorization.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Cruze', 'The Chevrolet Cruze uses the GM Global-A security platform, featuring high-security flip-keys or proximity smart keys. It utilizes Hitag 3 or ID46 transponder chips that are easily programmable through the OBDII port in about 10 minutes. The system is very consistent, though early models are known for ignition cylinder failures where the key becomes stuck or won''t turn. If programming fails, check the BCM for any active ''Antitheft'' codes that might be blocking the learning sequence.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Equinox', 'The Chevrolet Equinox is a high-volume crossover that has transitioned from ''Circle Plus'' transponders to the Global-A and Global-B proximity systems. Programming for most years is standard and efficient, taking about 12 minutes through the OBDII port. Newer 2023+ models utilize the Global-B architecture, which requires CAN-FD capable tools and often an online handshake. Always verify if the vehicle has a ''Keyed'' ignition or ''Push Button Start'' as they require different mechanical and transponder protocols.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Express', 'The Chevrolet Express van utilizes the standard GM transponder system, evolving from early Passlock to ''Circle Plus'' (PK3+) and current encrypted variants. This is a very robust and well-supported system for locksmiths, with key additions taking less than 10 minutes in most cases. The mechanical keys are standard GM cuts and are usually very easy to duplicate or originate. pro tip: Check the BCM/fuse box in the passenger footwell if you experience communication issues, as moisture and corrosion are common in commercial vans.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|HHR', 'The Chevrolet HHR uses the GM ''Circle Plus'' transponder architecture with a Philips ID46 chip, similar to the Cobalt of the same era. Programming is very reliable through the OBDII port and typically takes less than 10 minutes to complete. The mechanical keys are standard GM 10-cut profiles that are easy to originate with a Lishi tool or by code. Be aware that the ignition lock cylinders were part of a major recall, so ensure the vehicle has the updated hardware before cutting new keys.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Impala', 'The Chevrolet Impala transitioned through multiple security generations, from VATS and Passlock to ''Circle Plus'' and modern Global-A proximity. The classic ''Circle Plus'' system (2006-2013) is extremely common and can be programmed in minutes through any professional tool. The newer generation (2014-2020) uses the Global-A platform with flip-keys or proximity smart keys. If you encounter a ''starting disabled'' message, a simple 10-minute ''Key Relearn'' sequence usually solves the issue on older models.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Malibu', 'The Chevrolet Malibu features security systems that evolved from early Passlock to modern Global-A and Global-B proximity architectures. Most modern Malibus use proximity smart keys with Hitag 3 transponders, which are programmed via a standard 12-minute OBDII sequence. The transmitter pocket is located in the center console or on the steering column shroud. Note that 2023+ models use Global-B security, requiring CAN-FD hardware for any immobilizer or key programming work.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Monte Carlo', 'The Chevrolet Monte Carlo shared its security architecture with the Impala, moving from Passlock to the ''Circle Plus'' PK3+ transponder system. It utilizes standard GM transponder keys that are easily programmed in under 10 minutes via the OBDII port. Most locksmith tools offer full coverage for ''All Keys Lost'' and key additions on this model. Mechanically, the locks are standard GM profiles and are generally easy to decode with a Lishi tool.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Silverado', 'The Chevrolet Silverado is a staple of the GM lineup, featuring security ranging from Passlock to the most advanced CAN-FD Global-B proximity systems. Newer models (2022+ Refreshed models) require CAN-FD adapters and often authorized server tokens for any security-related work. Older ''Circle Plus'' (2007-2013) models are extremely common and easy to program in minutes. pro tip: On modern Silverados, the transmitter pocket location can vary, so check the center console tray or the cup holder if the key isn''t detected.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Sonic', 'The Chevrolet Sonic utilizes the GM Global-A security platform, featuring both high-security flip-keys and proximity smart keys. It uses Hitag 3 or ID46 transponder chips that are easily programmed through the OBDII port in about 10-12 minutes. The system is very consistent across all trim levels and is well-supported by all professional locksmith tools. Watch for ''Immobi'' light issues, which can sometimes be triggered by an weak battery or an aftermarket alarm system.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Spark', 'The Chevrolet Spark uses a compact version of the GM Global-A security system, using high-security flip-keys or proximity smart keys. Programming is straightforward via OBDII, typically following the standard GM 12-minute learn sequence for new keys. Success rates are high, but ensure the battery is healthy as the small Spark battery can drain quickly during key learning. If ''All Keys Lost,'' it is sometimes necessary to perform a full system reset to clear any existing ''lock-out'' status in the BCM.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Suburban', 'The Chevrolet Suburban features robust security platforms consistent with the Tahoe and Silverado, moving from ''Circle Plus'' to Global-A and modern Global-B. 2021+ models utilize the Global-B architecture, which requires CAN-FD adapters and professional-level security authorization. Older models are very common and easily programmed through the OBDII port on any major locksmith platform. Always verify if the vehicle has a ''Factory Alarm'' as it can interfere with the proximity synching process if not handled correctly.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Tahoe', 'The Chevrolet Tahoe uses the same high-security platforms as the Silverado and Suburban, evolving from early Passlock to modern Global-B proximity. Global-B models (2021+) require CAN-FD hardware and often an active connection to GM''s security database for authorized programming. Older ''Circle Plus'' systems are straightforward and can be handled in under 10 minutes by most technicians. pro tip: In proximity-equipped Tahoes, the transmitter pocket is often located in the center console or underneath the cup holder liners.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Trailblazer', 'The Chevrolet Trailblazer spans two distinct architectures: the early 2000s models with Passlock II and the modern 2021+ models with Global-A or Global-B proximity. Modern Trailblazers are programmed through the OBDII port using standard GM routines, with some years moving toward the more secure Global-B system. Older Trailblazers are prone to ignition switch failures, which can cause erratic security lights and intermittent starting. Always check for a ''Security'' message on the cluster, as it is the most reliable indicator of an immobilizer fault on this model.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Traverse', 'The Chevrolet Traverse utilize the GM Global-A and Global-B proximity architectures for its security needs. It features proximity smart keys that are generally well-supported by all major professional locksmith tools. Programming focuses on a standard 12-minute learn cycle through the OBDII port, requiring the proximity key to be in the transmitter pocket. Be aware that newer 2023+ models are likely to have the Global-B architecture, necessitating CAN-FD hardware for any key-related operations.', '2026-02-05');
INSERT OR REPLACE INTO vehicle_descriptions (vehicle_key, description, generated) VALUES ('Chevrolet|Trax', 'The Chevrolet Trax uses the GM Global-A and modern Global-B platforms, utilizing high-security flip-keys and proximity smart keys. Programming is a standard GM procedure, taking about 12 minutes through the OBDII port for most generations. The transmitter pocket is located in the center console; placing the key there is essential for the car to recognize it during learning. Watch for battery drain on these compact SUVs during the proximity learning sequence, and use a booster if necessary.', '2026-02-05');
